document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Science

29D183FAC7A84F40BF7D04FB5B62F7BF.description:
Complex and advanced learning standards in Ohio’s New
Learning Standards are not included in the extended
standards.

AF246472A7054AFD9BAF3B460E065796.description:
Manipulate a variety of magnets and identify that magnets
can have different strengths.

E4FED193B4EA4944AC7F70787BC72897.description:
List products in the home that contain magnets (e.g.,
computers, motors, stud finders, purse clasps, cell
phones, refrigerator magnets).

18F8A66FAB6D45EBA773943551811AA5.description:
Explain that different magnets produce different magnetic
fields (e.g., use paper clips to investigate how far away
from a magnet the paperclip can be and still be pulled to
the magnet comparing various magnets).

3B397555FC11486A81E1453185742FB9.description:
Describe that flowing electricity can produce a magnetic
field (e.g., electromagnet).

B4FE2F9AC1D545219E26F2DC0AA9209A.description:
Demonstrate
that different magnets
have different sized
magnetic fields.

4349C2BAC76C46C7A0CD02F96D7ECCB8.description:
Apply a
real-life example
demonstrating
the strength of
magnetic fields
(e.g., explore how
many paper clips a
weak magnet can
hold up versus a
strong magnet).

AEA9C79226B4491FB77603D9A02EEBEC.description:
Identify the requirements of a complete current circuit.
(e.g., observe or construct a circuit with a battery, wires,
a bulb and a switch, see what happens as the switch is
opened and closed).

A1054C8FBBF64FBD82BB46D6E27A86FE.description:
Define materials which transfer electricity easily (metals)
as conductors.

D2C74F32AA654B78A3ADAD050C6D157B.description:
Explain that a circuit requires a complete path (closed
loop) of conducting materials.

1EEED2E5EA334C06B984C69622973772.description:
Given materials construct a circuit which operates an
electric device (e.g., light bulb, motor, buzzer).

E02CF0F38C4D4FB0A2F145A88A997E97.description:
Explain that not all circuits behave exactly alike (e.g.,
observe the brightness of the bulb in a simple circuit, see
how the brightness changes if a second bulb is added in
series or in parallel).

9B9911613E424AD994A06B18A2727738.description:
Complete
a direct current
circuit (e.g., closing
a switch to initiate
flow).

092055227CAF4A6AB50AEA7850CDB242.description:
Identify the
required parts of a
circuit.

46A66C562BEB4F9CB936D74F2012912E.description:
DC Circuits
• Ohm’s law
• Series circuits
• Parallel circuits
• Mixed circuits
• Applying conservation of
charge and energy (junction
and loop rules)

3E53A60FE54F42EDB1FC11D9F8EB4124.description:
Recognize that an electric field can cause a change to
objects brought into the field (e.g., makes paper shreds
move).

88C55A48684D4247A439989B0B540C75.description:
Describe how the effect of an electric field varies
depending on the charge of the object that enters the field
(like charges repel and unlike charges attract).

34065C017452430E937582A1864E68E9.description:
Explain that an electric field can exist around an object
(e.g., bring a balloon that has been rubbed on hair near
small pieces of paper to observe that an electric field
exists around the balloon).

63775B41497B4BB8AEA12230B8083D15.description:
Identify
a field as an area
around an object.

8DB090F451F048D39C62B85D454A0532.description:
Label a
model or picture
indicating an electric
field.

D360F82FB03B4BB1869083433B130C7F.description:
Recognize the
effect of an electric
field around a
positively or
negatively charged
object (e.g., like
charges repel, and
opposite charges
attract).

F17233701CEE491A8A30C64CA1CE13EA.description:
Electric Fields and
Electric Potential Energy

4C4EF6E8B696486683F1DDED7CCB65FD.description:
Complex and advanced learning standards in Ohio’s New
Learning Standards are not included in the extended
standards.

80E3ABA4481C45ABAAE99E39BF16E7D8.description:
Recognize that a plus sign (+) is used to show a positive
charge.

17AD1577C8864DFBBFE5AC78F1773778.description:
Recognize that a minus sign (-) is used to show a negative
charge.

0842328D358B464B9E0E399EE86E9970.description: Identify that opposite charges attract each other.

4A0B8C2328FA44EFAC809C6178C9005C.description:
Describe that electrons have a negative charge and are
located in the outer portions of atoms.

EAFC0E120E7C4AA1BE0F786042602130.description:
Explain that electrons can move from one object to
another when they are rubbed together (e.g., rubbing a
balloon on hair, rubbing a glass rod with silk) and that one
object will end up with a positive charge and the other with
a negative charge

2A0180D654AE4A2DA82DB2C8A74F56D2.description:
Give examples of different ways charges can move (e.g.,
touching a metal surface, feet rubbing on carpet, a static
charged balloon held near hair).

151D3F022A1A4CD3B943A8CA77EFCC8E.description:
Relate the
symbols (+, -) to
their corresponding
charge.

A91184C40F6F45BFAE9CAF185B43C728.description:
Understand
that objects can have
charges which can
be either negative or
postitive.

5B1CD5938B0243BF81F0F6EF7B9DD092.description:
Recognize that
charges can
transfer from one
object to another in
different ways.

E28FD10D18C54238B74C758A6348DE98.description:
Recognize that a ray diagram is a way to show the path of
light using arrows.

856389506BA545C687B542E2376EDFEE.description:
Given a ray diagram, trace the path of light from its source
to where it exits the diagram.

A4D88D98F10441D8895815C928DDDE7F.description:
Identify that light reflects at the same angle it enters a
mirror (e.g., shine a laser pointer into a mirror at different
angles and see where it reflects).

8BEBB61E359E43A0B27C8B835048039E.description:
Describe that different lenses affect light in different ways
(e.g., investigate the path of light as it passes through a
variety of lenses).

0CB2BEDCBF2A4C38A380ADB70847F13D.description:
Given a partially completed ray diagram showing light
reflecting off a mirror fill in the missing ray (could select
from a set of options).

39008B2315F149C18D6C9AAABCA5A45D.description:
Given a partially completed ray diagram showing light
passing through a lens fill in the missing ray(s) (could
select from a set of options).

7C74F8E844284241850CAB09D743C282.description:
While observing a light beam interacting with a lens or
mirror, construct or select a ray diagram that depicts the
observations.

7614CB8394BA482D97B74D671F583AF4.description:
Complete a
simple ray diagram to
show at what angle a
wave is reflected off a
surface.

FB83D48568C649169CEFF00EB17E25C6.description:
Create
a ray diagram
showing the path
of a light wave.

C0DFA1BF1E49447F9741576BF20050C8.description:
Light Phenomena
• Ray diagrams (propagation
of light)
• Law of reflection (equal
angles)
• Snell’s law
• Diffraction patterns
• Wave – particle duality of
light
• Visible spectrum and color
• Visible spectrum and color

62645281983E4A648C522429D7DE2A58.description:
Describe different reflected images (e.g., examine mirrors
to see the reflections produced). Compare and contrast
the images with the original objects, describing, size,
orientation and distance from mirror.

1AE249DF06B447E494FE75EE0F413451.description:
Describe that white light is made of a variety of colors
of light (e.g., manipulate prisms to see the separation of
white light as it passes from air to glass and back to air).

8B7DC07F3ED54ACDBF80E718EF616F6E.description: Explain why a stick looks crooked in a glass of water.

7B7FDA34662A4512B5056E81FACD74DD.description:
Describe the relationship between the medium light is
passing through and its speed. Recognize that light travels
fastest in a vacuum.

FF012F5628034358A3A5A4C0261B8BB6.description:
Identify the
reflection of light in
a mirror.

F1993094E3CC4147AA5EA5A475A564BD.description:
Identify
what results from
light traveling into
a different medium
(e.g., dispersion
into colors – prism,
apparent location of
a pencil is different
from actual location -
water).

A2849FE9598046B289F7DB3E6F1C86A9.description:
Compare
the speeds at
which light waves
travel in different
mediums.

DCEA95DC817F41E3AA4F91001C89D346.description:
Wave Properties
• Conservation of energy
• Reflection
• Refraction
• Interference
• Diffraction

DD09AEBE2D324C4FA47D649EB0128A89.description:
Define nuclear energy as energy stored in the nucleus of
an atom.

92292F650DBA43C6B2F5532431BD7DD7.description:
Identify that the energy in the nucleus is transferred to a
new location when a nucleus is broken or two nuclei are
combined.

FBC6B138593A4CFDBE97620335B2B301.description:
Describe that nuclei are being combined in stars (including
our sun).

A16266F94A2F468480AF4CD2D6847A8B.description:
Trace or describe the changes nuclear power plants use
to capture the energy released when a nucleus breaks
apart and use it to generate electricity.

F5BD3773327D43DF85D4333F0B0BA544.description:
List some ways humans use nuclear energy (e.g., power
submarines, generate electricity, nuclear medicine).

05AF65AE7DA84A169535C9CE32F547F1.description:
Define nuclear fission as breaking a nucleus and nuclear
fusion and combining two nuclei.

5333B705DB924D9390E1F2EBCC9BB8DD.description:
Identify
nuclear energy as
a type of energy.

B59EF82CF53349B28476C597FE3AD816.description:
Describe ways
people use nuclear
energy.

105A0B47016B4F4892C4EF28BBD80397.description:
Identify
types of nuclear
energy (e.g.,
fission and fusion).

3E7E4705B9404812A2B080BADF53FDAF.description:
Describe that energy can change form or location but
is not created or destroyed (e.g., investigate energy
transformations in systems such as electric circuits or balls
colliding to see that energy changes location or changes
from one form to another, but still exists).

9A0D5B3169C246BE88334BDF751AF875.description:
Describe that there is always the same amount of energy
before and after a change.

C072014F34AC4455868DF58E67AC7C68.description:
Explain that friction always changes some energy to heat
(e.g., rub hands together to feel heat generated from
friction).

1A4BE3AF131C464185053ABCEB2B7613.description:
Recognize that heat energy can transfer into the
environment around a system (e.g., air) and no longer be
noticeable.

26EE877CC42F4392AEC2A485690FAD31.description:
Explain that the energy from objects slowing down is not
disappearing because the friction when two substances
move against each other changes kinetic energy to heat
which dissipates into the environment.

08F1A2DA3736405C9CBE66A0CB0DC201.description:
Identify that when heat is transferred to the air it is not
gone, but that it is no longer usable in the system.

1D188BF023924AB1838EDF97A50A6383.description:
Given a situation involving energy transfer and/or
transformation explain the flow of energy in the system.

1851A265300A489CB0E259D6886F0A7F.description:
Identify
that energy cannot
be created or
destroyed.

9B5B5ADB3E5D41ACBF6F11A92C937E7C.description:
Explain that
energy changes forms
but the total amount is
the same before and
after a transfer.

5F08CF96A8324218BD8C2F0237450677.description:
Given
situation, describe
where the energy
has gone (e.g.,
a car rolling
down hill has
energy changing
from potential to
kinetic).

95E216FCC3BD477E9424A140CED755F5.description:
Explain that work is done when something is moved a
distance by a force (except when the motion and the force
are at right angles to each other).

920EEDC190884BB1AD49BF2D735CA06B.description: Calculate work by multiplying force by the distance moved.

F9772D6D7A1B4607AC9B0883FFBAB3F8.description: Identify that power is work done per unit of time.

87CF92FD86C24880AB66E8766F2C122F.description:
Describe a way to increase the power of a machine (e.g.,
pedal a bicycle faster because more work is being done
during each minute of time).

A844C4665C8742CD8BB507E993D7A18C.description:
Calculate power by dividing the work done by the amount
of time needed to do that work.

8B8604579B4D435FB0365536F9821B01.description:
Compare graphs of work vs. time for two machines or
situations. Identify the steeper slope as having more
power.

448399B51B4940BF8EF27A95A03A2415.description:
Describe
the relationship
between work and
power (pedaling a
bicycle, lifting different
weights). More work
in a shorter period
of time equals more
power.

CD050F75B09E4B19852ABAD809C8F6BA.description:
Chart
the relationship
between work and
power.

470F043D1EE346528C26DAEC928FBF98.description: Recognize that a coiled material is a spring.

EA2ADDBC9A5E4E908B04192A44F2AF0C.description:
Identify objects that you use in daily activities that contain
springs (e.g., beds, cars, pens, toys).

661B09A0F2084F3EA482AFE1D8C55949.description:
Identify that stretched or compressed springs have elastic
potential energy (i.e., can do work).

7F9625FAF16B4747A97AE2E675BC01A9.description:
Describe that some springs are more easily compressed
than others (e.g., investigate various springs).

FAD705A5EC67403BA37C2FF2BAF8AC4D.description:
Design a way to use a compressed spring to move an
object (e.g., launcher in a pinball machine).

24CD5E122D79447596A8986FEC9B07B7.description:
Identify a location in the real-world where the addition of a
spring could improve the function of a tool.

9C73D0258EE34B8D8719EE3D5E754672.description:
Identify
where springs are
used in everyday
life.

3452150A9AAD48B88D436A3A759D0B3F.description:
Manipulate
a variety of
springs and make
observations (e.g.,
from inside of a
ball point pen, from
toys).

763083B74F974384B960332A9272E26A.description:
Investigate
how the use of a
spring can improve
the efficiency of a
tool (e.g., a shock
absorber in a car or a
ball point pen).

B1C9CDA152EB4AC887E4526BBCC70C0A.description:
Compare
the distance that two
different springs can
stretch or can be
compressed.

62EAE07855C34D01B20ADDB50CBE470C.description:
Identify
a real-world
scenario where
the use of a spring
might improve
the efficiency or
performance of a
tool.

0F8AEFEF035740D19A09CC7063D560AC.description:
Given a
spring stretched
various amounts,
identify when it has
the most potential
energy.

E6B91958D5754A728A7DD3B26491CCAC.description: Explain that all objects exert a gravitational force.

4BA6E01330EC40A19D576A3ACC583BED.description:
Describe the relationship between size and gravitational
force (larger objects exert more force).

9E3E868192D14D8F8E77F6590618DCC4.description:
Describe the relationship between distance and
gravitational force (closer objects exert more force).

72E7B589F7F3454E88FE03FBF01FBFCA.description:
Recognize that when two interacting objects are at a
distance from one another gravitational potential energy
exists.

5F356755D8F5452E9E450008EC378851.description:
Describe that gravitational potential energy exists as a
field around attracting objects. As the distance between
objects is increased energy is transferred into the field
and potential energy increases. As the distance between
objects is decreased energy is transferred out of the field
and potential energy decreases.

E0E0E8CF32704CC09BF5CFE194AA3B54.description:
Describe
that the gravitational
force between two
objects depends on
the distance between
them and their
masses.

0B45AD1D61F049FAA887742657E196F0.description:
Explain
that when
two attracting
objects are at
a distance from
each other there
is gravitational
potential energy
present.

F4C0A6D650D04E1AB92ABE0299E263A1.description:
Engage with inclined planes by exploring the motion a
various objects down a slope.

64C4C94ED98248E9B29FB7BCE3D08CE0.description: Define an incline as a sloped surface.

51EE63E36B614D39927E42A6CB7E9124.description:
Identify examples of objects and substances moving down
inclines (e.g., water flowing down a river, sled sliding down
a hill, balls rolling down ramps).

458CDCF61B8541B0AC607BC0AEDA0B6F.description:
Identify the force of gravity as the agent causing things to
move down inclined surfaces .

CE388D8D3C2345D58FDF7A6415A1EE93.description:
Given objects in circular motion (e.g., ball on string, planet
in orbit, ferris wheel) identify the agent and direction of the
force causing each circular motion.

6A2EF6A1B2F443728774C28D57BAACEE.description:
Describe what occurs when the force acting toward the
center of a circle is removed (e.g., watch videos such as
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dxmedyNZ_8s that
show what happens when a centripetal force is removed).

9868D62DF8B64E04AB8B643272DD01A3.description:
Recognize
that gravity is the
force that creates
motion down an
incline.

028A9883B7924E9D9C4B7DC278F61C94.description:
Indicate
the direction of the
centripetal force of
an object moving in a
circular motion (e.g.,
ball being swung on a
string).

4DF5086DB66D42BDB116BE47AB2C33ED.description:
Identify
the force that, if
removed from an
object moving in
a circular motion,
would cause the
object to move in a
straight line.

5E3047D6D50B4CEC84C5A692DFD336B4.description:
Forces in Two
Dimensions
• Adding vector forces
AND
P.F.7 Momentum, Impulse,
and Conservation of
Momentum
• Motion down inclines
• Centripetal forces and
circular motion

BA8E462A496D45F186998E70C7235A8F.description:
Drop a marble through various fluids (e.g., air, oil, syrup,
water) and time how long it takes each to fall an equal
distance.

292AF5725D1346809EB4E4260EAE0959.description:
Describe air resistance and drag as forces that slow
objects moving in fluids (liquids and gases).

F0878CA1BF9242579665C38C31724140.description:
Describe which types of fluids allow materials to pass
through them most easily.

14A41A6EB4A54009B247D79B95177367.description:
Explain how air resistance and drag affect the motion of
falling objects.

5EB3918392DF478BBA3152102289624B.description:
Explain how air resistance and drag affect the motion
of objects moving through fluids (e.g., boats, kites,
swimmers, airplanes).

55710D71A3FB4E8499A81696E50C64C5.description:
Drop the
same object in
air and into a
variety of liquids
with different
viscosity and make
observations (e.g.,
oil, honey, and
water).

87FBC62A38A84BA79F6D610B7BC76B0F.description:
When given
an object, make
a prediction of its
motion and rate of fall
when dropped in the
air and a variety of
liquids.

FBBF1E0B138F44E58921FA4B14AAA11B.description:
Through
investigation,
determine the rate
of fall of an object
in air and a variety
of liquids.

5FD9141C39A745628008BBD546E66E2E.description: Explain that frictions slows moving objects.

BB61B67209A249698937DFA3A69903AF.description:
Describe how different surfaces result in different amount
of friction (e.g., slide a block down a ramp with different
surfaces (wood, plastic, vegetable oil on the surface,
sandpaper) to observe differences in speed)).

5BEAB247F26B4640A3549CD333FA7F3E.description:
Identify ways to make a surface easier to slide across
(sanding, adding a lubricant).

6592AAADE99348E596C8DABD9481D769.description:
Identify a way to move a heavy cabinet across a floor
(adding wheels, sliding on a blanket).

7CC3DF5BDC9B4123985884D7BFB4A723.description:
Order a given set of surfaces from produces the most
friction to produces the least friction.

EB0F1F730F4A403E851308D620194B57.description:
Define kinetic friction as contact between two moving
surfaces.

6809D4F063DB48AAB0B312FA02EAB283.description:
Define static friction as contact between two stationary
surfaces which must be overcome to start an object
moving.

1E7148DEF1FC4191A0ADADCF8556FC10.description:
Recognize
that diverse
surface types
cause friction
differently.

BF8920771E254E3C86996DA52A5AD62D.description:
Investigate
friction as it relates
to moving an object
(e.g., sliding furniture
over different types of
flooring).

AE1266C1DB2F479495A2F31A9E18E086.description:
Organize
the surface types
from “causes the
most friction” (most
difficult to push) to
“causes the least
amount of friction”
(easiest to push).

CB7BDB844FFE4D9BAA7B98732A0EC0DF.description:
Recognize that things which can stretch are elastic
objects.

D7DDBD2FA1D140DE963797E6775FAB4D.description:
Distinguish elastic from non-elastic objects. From a set
of objects (or images) select the items that are elastic
objects.

AB392E8043974A4984C06C454FC0AC2E.description:
Recognize that not all elastic objects stretch the same
amount (e.g., use a variety of different fabrics (denims),
rubber bands or bungee cords to illustrate this point).

F4B3E9D995DA42C49FEA6630CB95644B.description:
Given two dissimilar objects, predict which one will stretch
the most.

83C2359E385349A59B9E248723761DFF.description:
Identify a way an elastic object could be used to make an
object move.

99B9C6EBBD9F422DB391F470151227E1.description:
Manipulate elastic objects (e.g., balloons, physical therapy
bands, bungee cords) and describe that the further each is
stretched the harder it is to keep stretching them (observe
safety considerations).

E498221899674749A0F07E67FE6AD0B3.description:
Design a device that uses elastic forces to propel an
object.

5A0B80A8B04C416F895386336EF473F9.description:
Manipulate
a variety of elastic
bands and other
elastic materials
and make
observations (e.g.,
rubber bands, hair
bands).

F80627E2B5BA47CA8279FCE94632B0A9.description:
Make a
prediction of the
elasticity of two
significantly different
elastic materials.

0866EFE255C24997BBB22E086D8A11C5.description:
Design a
device that would
propel an object
using elastic
materials (e.g.,
rubber band cars).

D3C6E8E8AA9A42E48671F1A50ACAF82C.description: Describe that objects fall because of the force of gravity.

1D9AC32B91C641FBBA56812C9E10EB06.description:
Identify that the force of gravity moves things (e.g., water
flowing down a river, fruit falling from trees, balls rolling
down ramps).

0001CE24DF4747B8975E9CF036DD595B.description:
Recognize that circular motion requires a force toward the
center of the circle (e.g., whirl a wiffle ball tied to a string in
a circle and watch what happens if you release the string,
observing appropriate safety precautions). Describe that
your hand was exerting an inward force on the string.

D20F68DAC8B5408DA0F467361D423BB6.description:
Describe that gravity from the sun makes planets travel in
circles and that Earth’s gravity does the same to satellites
including our moon.

BE309F26D4E04FA7BCD829FC2B33EDDC.description:
Explain that more massive objects exert greater
gravitational forces (e.g., Earth pulls on an object more
than the moon does).

EC364C50D9FD433E8ED18C11954E6C3B.description:
Recognize that
gravity is the force
that keeps planets
and satellites in
circular orbits

61A7F48C1B804071A6697CD36383866D.description:
Explain
the relationship
between mass and
gravitational pull.

3C8E3DB808394F36890B5F1EF693EDB4.description:
Roll a ball into a stationary ball and describe what happens to
the motion of the balls (first one slows down, second one starts
moving).

11D45FB37CA84859AFA2A365B1E856A4.description:
Roll the ball from different angles and describe how the direction
that the second ball moves changes.

B35AC6F087B6450BAEE94CE19EB853DA.description:
Roll two balls, carts or toy cars toward each other and describe
their motions after colliding.

21D7365FBF09416599C8CA92333D96EC.description:
State a general rule for what happens when two moving objects
collide.

A57A4076813E427DAE53814066639147.description:
Recognize that when you sit on a chair you are pushing down on
the chair and the chair is holding you up.

29DDC6936DF7462F91442621D4FE6FB3.description:
Use Newton’s Third Law to identify that an object pulls or pushes
back whenever you pull or push on it (e.g., pull on a rope tied to
a stationary object to feel action/reaction forces; explain when
you exert a force on the rope the rope exerts an equal force back
on you which you can feel as the rope pulling you).
